I am frustrated that to no fault of my own I slipped on ice at the front door entering the school where I teach on 1/31/23. I am a certified educator, but hired as a contractor for my position by a medical staffing agency.  My PN&R doctor stated clearly that I would be compensated for my injury (concussion), if not by the agency that employs me, but by OH BWC.  This was not accurate information, as I found out after a check for less than I make in one day arrived in the mail weeks later.  In seeking clarification I have found little, and the school system that employs me did not seem to take corrective action to ensure the problem did not/ will not occur in the future.  Seven weeks after the accident, I will finally have an opportunity to begin therapy on a concern that if addressed earlier, may not still be occurring at night as I get up and down. Ultimately, I missed almost two weeks of FT work at $42 an hour, and another week of work where I was on doctor prescribed restricted 'light duty.' While I am thankful I was not severely injured with a skull fracture or broken bones, a struggle to understand how I am to absorb the cost of lost wages for an injury that could have been prevented had someone simply salted before staff and students arrived.  Lesson learned; as I now keep my own bag of salt in my car.  I will also add that because I have been dealing with fraud related concerns for multiple years, the series of events that occurred at both the ER and the difficulty I have had while seeking answers, forces me to ask the question if fraud related concerns may still be a relevant in Cleveland where I have faithfully served in multiple school systems as a certified educator for years.
